# Card-trader DOMAIN reasoning — the deductive business-semantics half of the KB.
# PROSE rules (harneskills.authoring.load_rules): plain deductive knowledge over card + market
# facts, the same deductive face as the thief riddle, now over business content. These are DOMAIN
# rules (card-specific), distinct from the generic policy/risk/preference machinery — they DERIVE
# facts (a card's value, the market's state, and a market-driven trading stance) that the generic
# machinery then acts on. Every conclusion is why-traceable back to the base facts.

# --- Card value: a card is valuable when it is rare AND sought-after (multi-step, composes) ---
?c is valuable when ?c is rare and ?c is in_demand
# a premium card is a valuable one in mint condition; a premium card is worth holding
?c is premium when ?c is valuable and ?c is mint
?c is worth_holding when ?c is premium

# --- Reasoning DERIVES the policy: a hot market makes selling worthwhile ---
# High demand + low supply => the market is hot; on a hot day, selling is ENCOURAGED. The deontic
# stance is DERIVED, not asserted — the substrate reasons its way to the policy. With the KB's
# `today outranks standing`, that derived encouragement OVERRIDES the standing `don't sell`, so a
# cold-market day honestly stays put (nothing to override the norm) while a hot day sells. Ask
# `why is selling possible` and the trace runs back through `market is hot` to demand and supply.
market is hot when demand is high and supply is low
sell encouraged today when market is hot
